library(tidyverse)
  • Read data, convert categorical variables to factors with descriptive labels, and remove the ‘female’ column.
female_labels <- c("male","female")
race_labels <- c("hispanic", "asian", "african-american", "white")
ses_labels <- c("low", "middle", "high")
schtyp_labels <- c("public","private")
prog_labels <- c("general", "academic", "vocational")
highschool <- read_csv("hsb2.csv", col_types = "dfffffddddd") %>%
  mutate(gender = factor(female, levels = c(0,1), labels = female_labels),
         race = factor(race, levels = c(1,2,3,4), labels = race_labels),
         ses = factor(ses, levels = c(1,2,3), labels = ses_labels),
         schtyp = factor(schtyp, levels = c(1,2), labels = schtyp_labels),
         prog = factor(prog, levels = c(1,2,3), labels = prog_labels)) %>%
  select(-female)

  • The code lm_all <- lm(math ~ ., data=highschool) creates a linear regression model that predicts the math scores (math) of students based on all other available variables in the highschool dataset.
  • In this context, math ~ . indicates that all other columns in the highschool data frame are used as predictors for the math scores.
lm_all <- lm(math ~ ., data=highschool)

select <- dplyr::select
# make a model which predicts price with no input variables
# effectively predicts using the mean
# the null model
model_min <- lm(math ~ 1, data=highschool )
# we can define the largest possible model using
# a dot . to mean include everything
# the full model
model_max <- lm(math ~ . , data=highschool )

scp <- list(lower = model_min, upper = model_max)

model_step <- stepAIC(model_min,
                      direction = "forward",
                      scope = scp,
                      trace=F # suppress printed output
                      )
summary(model_step)

Applying a multiple regression

Let’s try to predict math score based on science score and gender:

model_v1 <- lm(math ~ science + gender,data=highschool)
summary(model_v1)

Call:
lm(formula = math ~ science + gender, data = highschool)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-25.5833  -5.2369   0.6198   4.6096  18.8215 

Coefficients:
             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)  21.00134    2.90036   7.241 9.78e-12 ***
science       0.59973    0.05252  11.418  < 2e-16 ***
genderfemale  0.98863    1.04545   0.946    0.345    
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 7.301 on 197 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.3988,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.3927 
F-statistic: 65.33 on 2 and 197 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The result is a fit formula:

\[ [mathscore] = 21.00 + 0.60 \times [science score] + 0.99 \times 1\lbrace gender = female\rbrace \]

where \(1\lbrace gender = female\rbrace = 1\) for female, \(1\lbrace gender = female\rbrace = 0\) for males, is what is known as an indicator function.

This is equivalent to the result:

Prediction formula for females:

\[ [math\ score] = 21.00 + 0.60 × [science\ score] + 0.99 \times 1 \\ = 21.99 + 0.60 × [science\ score] \]

  • In this way we see that being female adds \(0.99\) marks to the predicted grade relative to being a male.

  • We can manually add these lines of best fit to a plot using ggplot’s geom_abline which adds a line of a given intercept \(a\) and gradient \(b\).

highschool %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(y=math, x=science, color=gender)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_abline(intercept=21.99, slope=0.60, color="lightblue") +
  geom_abline(intercept=20.99, slope=0.60, color="pink")

  • Note that alternatively we can use predict to calculate fitted predictions automatically.

  • To do this we generate new dataframes, formatted as the original dataframe but with the values we want to use as input predictions.

# note we must match the factor format of the gender column
# so add in the relevant mutate function call
highschool_f_demo <- tibble( science = seq(0,100,0.1), gender = "female") %>%
mutate(gender = factor(gender, levels=c("male","female")))
highschool_m_demo <- tibble( science = seq(0,100,0.1), gender = "male") %>%
mutate(gender = factor(gender, levels=c("male","female")))
highschool_f_demo$math <- predict(model_v1, newdata = highschool_f_demo)
highschool_m_demo$math <- predict(model_v1, newdata = highschool_m_demo)
  • Now we have two dataframes with science scores running from 0 to 100, with female and male gender respectively along with predicted math columns.
  • This then makes it easy to plot the results (note we set the default mapping in the ggplot command on the first line):
ggplot(mapping = aes(y=math, x=science, color=gender)) +
  geom_point(data = highschool) +
  geom_line(data = highschool_m_demo) +
  geom_line(data = highschool_f_demo)

  • We see that in this model the effect of gender (adding \(0.99\) to prediction for females) is independent of the science score.

  • We can make a second model where we add formula term gender*science to allow an interaction term between gender and science score.

model_v2 <- lm(math ~ science + gender + gender*science,data=highschool)
summary(model_v2)

lm(formula = math ~ science + gender + gender * science, data = highschool)

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Multiple R-squared:  0.4027,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.3935 
F-statistic: 44.04 on 3 and 196 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The result is a fit formula:

\[ [math\ score] = 23.89 + 0.55 \times [science\ score] − \]

\[ 5.18 \times 1\lbrace gender = female \rbrace + 0.11 \times 1\lbrace gender = female\rbrace \times [science\ score] \]

This is equivalent to the result:

Prediction formula for males:

$$ [math score] = 23.89 + 0.55 - 5.18

+ 0.11 $$

\[ = 23.89 + 0.55 \times [science\ score] \]

Prediction formula for females:

\[ [math\ score] = 23.89 + 0.55 \times [science\ score] - 5.18 \times 1 + 0.11 \times 1 \times [science\ score] \]

\[ = (23.89 - 5.18) + (0.55 + 0.11) \times [science\ score] \\ = 18.71 + 0.66 \times [science\ score] \]

We can copy the code above to plot the predictions for males and females over a range of science scores:

highschool_f_demo <- tibble( science = seq(0,100,0.1), gender = "female") %>%
  mutate(gender = factor(gender, levels=c("male","female")))
highschool_m_demo <- tibble( science = seq(0,100,0.1), gender = "male") %>%
  mutate(gender = factor(gender, levels=c("male","female")))

highschool_f_demo$math <- predict(model_v2, newdata = highschool_f_demo)
highschool_m_demo$math <- predict(model_v2, newdata = highschool_m_demo)

ggplot(mapping = aes(y=math, x=science, color=gender)) +
  geom_point(data = highschool) +
  geom_line(data = highschool_m_demo) +
  geom_line(data = highschool_f_demo)

  • We can see that when we have an interaction between a numerical and categorical variables we are allowing the slope of the fitted lines to be category dependent.

  • In this case we should consider the statistical significance of the difference between the modelled fit between male and female scores.

  • In this case the cofficients associated with gender (and the interaction term between gender and science score) have p-values above \(0.05\), the \(95\%\) significance level.

  • This means from this analysis we would conclude that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that when science score is used to predict math scores gender has no influence.

Alternative way to view results

  • An alternative way to view the results of a model is to plot fitted predictions vs actual values To do this we can use the predict function to add a ..._pred column to our data for plotting.
  • If the predictions were perfect, then all the data points would lie on the line \(y=x\) and the distance (vertical distance if we put predicted values on the \(y\)-axis and vice versa) from each point to this line show us the size of the residuals.
highschool$math_pred <- predict(model_v1, newdata=highschool)

highschool %>% ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(y=math_pred, x=math)) +
  geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1)

  • We can see if a full model reduces the residuals. (Note we must exclude the prediction column from the model).
model_full <- lm(math ~ . - math_pred, data=highschool)
summary(model_full)

  • The coefficients here are for the linear (1st order polynomial) component and the quadratic (2nd order polynomial) component.
  • If we fit a polynomial and find the coefficient of the highest polynomial term is not significant (p-value > chosen significance level), then we can say that there is no evidence that that our regression function requires a term of that order.
  • In this case the 2nd order term is statistically significant, reflecting the fact that a quadratic curve better fits the relationship.

Overfitting

When a regression model captures noise, it means the model is trying to explain these random deviations as if they were part of the underlying pattern. This typically happens in the following situations:

  • High Degree Polynomial Regression: Using a very high degree polynomial to fit data that has an underlying linear or low-degree polynomial relationship. The model bends and twists to fit every single data point, including the noisy ones.

  • Too Many Features: Including too many predictors in the model, some of which may not have a real association with the outcome but appear to due to random chance in the sample data.

  • Insufficient Data: Having too few data points relative to the complexity of the model, leading the model to fit the peculiarities of the small sample rather than the true relationship.

Consequences

  • The main consequence of capturing noise is poor model generalization. While the model may show excellent performance on the training data, it performs poorly on new, unseen data because it has learned to fit the noise rather than the true signal.

-Visual Representation In a visual sense, capturing noise means the fitted regression line (or curve) will be very wiggly and closely follow each data point, as opposed to a smoother line that captures the general trend.

true_relationship <- function(x,sigma=0.1){
  1-x-x^2+x^3+rnorm(length(x),sd=sigma)
}

x <- runif(200,min=-1,max=1)

set.seed(1)
y <- true_relationship(x)

data_all <- data.frame(y,x)

ggplot(data=data_all,
       aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point()

This is all the data, but we typically only have access to a subset of the data.

set.seed(1)

observations <- sample(1:dim(data_all)[1],20)

x <- data_all$x[observations]
y <- data_all$y[observations]

data_a <- data.frame(y,x)

ggplot(data=data_a,
       aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point()

What if we fit a linear regression to this data?

lm_a_1 <- lm(y~x,data=data_a)

data_a$y_1 <- predict(lm_a_1,data_a)

ggplot(data=data_a,
       aes(x=x,y=y)) +

  geom_smooth(method="lm",
              formula=y~x,

Preventing Overfitting:

  • Cross-Validation: Use techniques like k-fold cross-validation to ensure the model generalizes well.

  • Regularization: Add penalties for larger coefficients (e.g., Lasso or Ridge regression).

  • Simpler Models: Use models that are appropriate for the complexity of the data.

  • Pruning: In decision trees, prune branches that have little importance.

  • Early Stopping: In iterative models like neural networks, stop training when performance on a validation set starts to degrade.
